This section appears to be a false representation of river conditions. The rise does not compare to Mountain or Keele and the trace after the bubbler trace is restored trends down, not up.The air temps start to drop below zero shortly after this peak. That can lead to bubbler failure and may be the reason for the false trace.

SRC to SRC.Carried to when Bubbler recovered and will grade all stage across this period as estimated.

-Section removed due to large SRC on next visit.-initially reset in April after thawing from frozen but as gauge was dead pressure could likely have been lost in line and water ingressed up the tube.-erratic trace after the spike seems like a clearing of the line and the values are between top and bottom of section are similar to SRC in May.

This steep drop through April is not supported by how this river usually responds through the under ice period. This is traditionally a fairly static time of stage change. Attribute this to the bubbler and line thawing
